<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,288,891]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,360,386]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[348,626,360,387]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scutifrons">
<emphasis box="[348,626,360,387]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Leptotyphlops scutifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from southern Africa and can be found throughout western and central 
<collectingCountry box="[291,373,396,422]" name="Angola" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Angola</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Marques, M. P. &amp; Ceriaco, L. M. P. &amp; Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M." box="[394,641,396,423]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 501" refId="ref38562" refString="Marques, M. P., Ceriaco, L. M. P., Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M. (2018) Diversity and distribution of the amphibians and terrestrial reptiles of Angola atlas of historical and bibliographic records (1840 - 2017). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, 65 (Supplement 2), 1 - 501." type="journal article" year="2018">
Marques 
<emphasis box="[506,568,396,422]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Ferreira, J. B." box="[665,841,396,423]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="111 - 117" refId="ref37152" refString="Ferreira, J. B. (1904) Reptis e amphibios de Angola da regiao ao norte do Quanza (Colleccao Newton 1903). Jornal de Sciencias Mathematicas Physicas e Naturaes, Segunda Serie, 7 (25), 111 - 117." type="journal article" year="1904">Ferreira (1904)</bibRefCitation>
cited adult specimens with “dark brown or black colour” of “ 
<taxonomicName box="[286,520,432,459]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scutifrons">
<emphasis box="[286,520,432,459]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Glauconia scutifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” from “Cazengo” and “Zembe” (
<collectingRegion box="[898,1174,432,459]" country="Angola" name="Kwanza Norte" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Kwanza Norte Province</collectingRegion>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Marques, M. P. &amp; Ceriaco, L. M. P. &amp; Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M." box="[1193,1436,432,459]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 501" refId="ref38562" refString="Marques, M. P., Ceriaco, L. M. P., Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M. (2018) Diversity and distribution of the amphibians and terrestrial reptiles of Angola atlas of historical and bibliographic records (1840 - 2017). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, 65 (Supplement 2), 1 - 501." type="journal article" year="2018">
Marques 
<emphasis box="[1298,1355,432,458]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
(2018)
</bibRefCitation>
tentatively considered them to be 
<taxonomicName box="[540,681,469,495]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scutifrons">
<emphasis box="[540,681,469,495]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">L. scutifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as 
<bibRefCitation author="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Broadley, S." box="[730,1059,468,495]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref34863" refString="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Broadley, S. (1999) A review of the African Worm Snakes from south of Latitude 12 ° S (Serpentes: Leptotyphlopidae). Syntarsus, 5, 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1999">Broadley &amp; Broadley (1999)</bibRefCitation>
had placed 
<taxonomicName box="[1200,1436,468,495]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scutifrons">
<emphasis box="[1200,1436,468,495]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Glauconia scutifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its synonymy and considered the species to occur in the Angolan plateau. We hereby follow this interpretation, as morphological analysis of the specimen proved inconclusive due to its poor conservation state. We were unable to properly review the characters that both 
<bibRefCitation author="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Broadley, S." box="[644,972,576,603]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref34863" refString="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Broadley, S. (1999) A review of the African Worm Snakes from south of Latitude 12 ° S (Serpentes: Leptotyphlopidae). Syntarsus, 5, 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1999">Broadley &amp; Broadley (1999)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Wallach, V." box="[1030,1346,576,603]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="3 - 78" refId="ref34905" refString="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Wallach, V. (2007) A revision of the genus Leptotyphlops in northeastern Africa and southwestern Arabia (Serpentes: Leptotyphlopidae). Zootaxa, 1408 (1), 3 - 78." type="journal article" year="2007">Broadley &amp; Wallach (2007)</bibRefCitation>
used to distinguish 
<taxonomicName box="[280,526,612,638]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[280,439,612,638]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Leptotyphlops</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in their revisions of the genus. 
<bibRefCitation author="Adalsteinsson, S. A. &amp; Branch, W. R. &amp; Trape, S. &amp; Vitt, L. J. &amp; Hedges, S. B." box="[871,1170,612,639]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 50" refId="ref33283" refString="Adalsteinsson, S. A., Branch, W. R., Trape, S., Vitt, L. J. &amp; Hedges, S. B. (2009) Molecular phylogeny, classification, and biogeography of snakes of the Family Leptotyphlopidae (Reptilia, Squamata). Zootaxa, 2244 (1), 1 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2244.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Adalsteinsson 
<emphasis box="[1034,1089,612,638]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
(2009)
</bibRefCitation>
in a more recent review of the 
<taxonomicName box="[221,422,648,674]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Leptotyphlopidae</taxonomicName>
, included 
<taxonomicName box="[534,671,649,675]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scutifrons">
<emphasis box="[534,671,649,675]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">L. scutifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a new tribe (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stejneger" authorityYear="1892" box="[841,1025,648,675]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Leptotyphlopini">Leptotyphlopini</taxonomicName>
) and suggested the use of “complex” to refer to it, as they found large sequence divergence between different samples of the species. The generic map the authors presented for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1843" box="[450,609,720,746]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[450,609,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Leptotyphlops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only included the Angolan provinces of Cuando Cubango and 
<collectingRegion box="[1349,1436,720,746]" country="Angola" name="Moxico" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Moxico</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Adalsteinsson, S. A. &amp; Branch, W. R. &amp; Trape, S. &amp; Vitt, L. J. &amp; Hedges, S. B." box="[159,447,756,783]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 50" refId="ref33283" refString="Adalsteinsson, S. A., Branch, W. R., Trape, S., Vitt, L. J. &amp; Hedges, S. B. (2009) Molecular phylogeny, classification, and biogeography of snakes of the Family Leptotyphlopidae (Reptilia, Squamata). Zootaxa, 2244 (1), 1 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2244.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Adalsteinsson 
<emphasis box="[325,381,756,782]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Marques, M. P. &amp; Ceriaco, L. M. P. &amp; Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M." box="[459,688,756,783]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 501" refId="ref38562" refString="Marques, M. P., Ceriaco, L. M. P., Blackburn, D. C. &amp; Bauer, A. M. (2018) Diversity and distribution of the amphibians and terrestrial reptiles of Angola atlas of historical and bibliographic records (1840 - 2017). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Series 4, 65 (Supplement 2), 1 - 501." type="journal article" year="2018">
Marques 
<emphasis box="[564,620,756,782]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, the authors also designated a new genus, 
<taxonomicName box="[1305,1429,756,782]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Namibiana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1305,1429,756,782]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Namibiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, to which they allocated the former “ 
<emphasis box="[555,655,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">rostratus</emphasis>
” group species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1843" box="[864,1023,792,818]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[864,1023,792,818]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Leptotyphlops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that 
<bibRefCitation author="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Wallach, V." box="[1079,1389,792,819]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="3 - 78" refId="ref34905" refString="Broadley, D. G. &amp; Wallach, V. (2007) A revision of the genus Leptotyphlops in northeastern Africa and southwestern Arabia (Serpentes: Leptotyphlopidae). Zootaxa, 1408 (1), 3 - 78." type="journal article" year="2007">Broadley &amp; Wallach (2007)</bibRefCitation>
had previously defined. The new genus is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[732,925,828,854]" name="Namibia" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">southwest Africa</collectingCountry>
, including 
<collectingCountry box="[1051,1137,828,854]" name="Angola" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Angola</collectingCountry>
. An integrative taxonomic revision is much needed to address the current difficulties of the group.
</paragraph>
